content.description:
Directly below Orange Lichen Line sits a gorgeous boulder with two excellent problems. Both sit start on the overhanging arete. 

  This line trends right through sloppers and crimps, finishing with compression moves on the far right arete, then into an easy but slightly heady slab finish.  

  Probably the best V4 in the state, if not the midwest. Folks gotta try this rig!

Directly below Orange Lichen Line sits a gorgeous boulder with two excellent problems. Both sit start on the overhanging arete. 

  This line moves up the sloppers on the left side of the boulder.

Gorgeous line in the tallest part of this crag. Will take gear after first 18' or so. Difficult moves off the ground and in the middle of the route interspersed with great holds and movement throughout. Proud line for a strong trad leader. Can be top roped by hiking to top and setting an anchor.
content.location: Obvious line in tallest section of wall. Angles left.

content.description: Cleaned and climbed summer 2015. Finger and hand crack with face holds and lots of feet. Find the Old Milwaukee can from the 70's at the top of the climb and dig out the register.
content.protection: Standard trad rack. Many gear options on top 2/3's of route. Small gear off the ground. Trees on top for anchor.
content.location: Far right side of cliff. Currently the only clean stripe on the rock.

content.description:
Climb through sustained and techy finger locks, using some occasional crimps along the way. Surprisingly pumpy and thoroughly enjoyable on excellent granite.

 The route is so named in honor of Randy who did the first ascent a year ago and only recently told folks about it. More mysterious though is the rusted fixed pin from an unknown aid climber who likely visited these lands before climbing gyms were even invented...many reputable climbing scholars tried casting light into this black hole of MN climbing history and no suitable theory has yet to emerge. A true enigma.
content.protection: small nuts and cams up to .5 purple BD
content.location: The obvious, thin finger crack to the 20 feet to the right of Orange Lichen Line.

content.description:
On the north west bay of Crane Lake is a wall that is 50'-60' tall and could host about 30 routes.  There would be some TR faces and trad leads.   

  The rock is fairly clean and well featured for climbing.  As far as I am aware there is no currently established routes on this wall.  It is one of the most accessible areas to get to by boat or canoe.   

  Just to the south east there is a National park camping area.  It is on the west side of the channel that leads to Sandpoint lake.
